> Think a dish like 'duck à l'orange' requires a plane ticket to France, or, at the very least, a reservation at the fanciest French restaurant in town? Think again! This luxurious meal can be whipped up from the comfort of your very own kitchen—in 40 minutes, no less. There's pan-seared duck glazed in a savory-sweet, thyme-flecked orange sauce, creamy duck fat mashed potatoes, and a mixed greens salad bursting with juicy orange segments, pickled shallot, and almonds. Take your taste buds on a trip—no passport required!

Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Yukon Gold potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Place in a #large pot{} with a few thyme sprigs (you'll use the rest in step 3) and enough salted water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil and cook until potatoes are tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

-- For a smoother texture, peel potatoes first.

Remove and discard @thyme{¼%ounce} sprigs. Reserve ½ cup potato cooking liquid, then drain and return potatoes to #pot.

Keep covered off heat until ready to mash.

Meanwhile, pat @duck breasts{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Place skin sides down in a #large nonstick pan{}. Cook over medium heat, carefully reserving fat in a #small bowl{} as it renders, until skin is crisp, ~{15-20%minutes}.

-- Lower heat if skin begins to brown too quickly.

While duck cooks, halve, peel, and thinly slice half the @shallot{1}. Toss sliced shallot in a separate small bowl with half the @red wine vinegar{5%tsp}, @sugar{1%tsp}, and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Strip thyme leaves from remaining sprigs until you have 1 tsp; roughly chop leaves.

Zest @orange{1} until you have 1 tsp. Halve orange; squeeze juice from one orange half into a #third small bowl{}. Peel remaining orange half; dice into ½-inch pieces.

-- For 4 servings, squeeze juice from two orange halves; peel and dice remaining orange.

To bowl with orange juice, stir in @apricot jam{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, half the orange zest, and remaining vinegar.

Once skin is crisp, flip duck in pan and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes}. Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest.

Add chopped thyme to same pan over medium heat and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in orange juice mixture and bring to a simmer. Cook until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Turn off heat.

Heat pot with drained potatoes over medium-low heat. Mash with @sour cream{2%tbsp} and @butter{1%tbsp} until smooth and creamy, adding splashes of reserved potato cooking liquid as needed.

Stir in reserved duck fat to taste. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

== Salad ==

In a #large bowl{}, combine shallot pickling liquid, @Dijon mustard{2%tsp}, a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp}, remaining orange zest, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Toss with @mixed greens{2%ounce}, pickled shallot, diced orange, and @almonds{½%ounce}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== To Serve ==

Slice duck crosswise. Divide between plates along with salad and mashed potatoes. Spoon sauce over duck and serve.